<BaseLayout
  title="About Strata"
  description="Strata preserves the reasoning, constraints, and downstream effects behind consequential decisions."
>
  <section class="case-header">
    <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
    <h1>Why Strata exists</h1>
    <p class="case-header__summary">
      Most case studies are shallow. They describe outputs, not decisions. They erase uncertainty
      and rejected paths. They flatten timelines into a fake linear story. Strata exists to fix that.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="case-body">
    <h2>The problem with most case studies</h2>
    <p>
      Conventional case studies optimize for presentation over reasoning. They tell you what shipped
      but not what was considered. They show the final answer but hide the constraints that shaped it.
      They make every outcome look inevitable.
    </p>
    <p>
      This creates a real gap: teams and individuals lose the ability to study decision quality over time.
      When you can't inspect how a decision was made, you can't learn from it, challenge it, or
      recognize when the same mistake is happening again.
    </p>

    <h2>The Strata framework</h2>
    <p>
      Every case study in Strata follows a structured narrative that preserves decision context:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Situation</strong> — what was happening and what triggered the need for a decision</li>
      <li><strong>Stakes</strong> — what was at risk and why the decision mattered</li>
      <li><strong>Constraints</strong> — the limitations that shaped the decision space</li>
      <li><strong>Options Considered</strong> — what alternatives were on the table</li>
      <li><strong>Decision</strong> — what the team chose</li>
      <li><strong>Why This Path Won</strong> — the reasoning behind the choice</li>
      <li><strong>Outcome</strong> — what happened after the decision shipped</li>
      <li><strong>What We Got Wrong</strong> — where the reasoning was flawed</li>
      <li><strong>Open Questions</strong> — what remains unresolved</li>
      <li><strong>Key Takeaways</strong> — generalizable lessons</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Principles</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Structure without sterility.</strong> The framework enforces a strong narrative skeleton
      but still allows expressive writing. The goal is to guide reflection, not to create forms.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Decisions over deliverables.</strong> The unit of value is the decision story, not the
      shipped artifact. What was built matters less than how the team reasoned about what to build.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Honesty is a feature.</strong> Sections about uncertainty, failure, and revised beliefs
      are mandatory. A case study that only reports success is incomplete.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Time matters.</strong> Before-and-after context is explicit. Timelines show how
      decisions evolved. Outcomes are measured after the dust settles, not at launch.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
